  "base_commit": "536ed07d2792b71948809a240a0dffe82ad99aee",
  "pr_number": 14932,
  "issue_number": 14810,
  "issue_title": "[Feature Request]: Implement embeddings in the Xinference Go driver",
  "issue_body": "### Self Checks\n\n- [x] I have searched for existing issues [search for existing issues](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/issues), including closed ones.\n- [x] I confirm that I am using English to submit this report ([Language Policy](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/issues/5910)).\n- [x] Non-english title submitions will be closed directly ( \u975e\u82f1\u6587\u6807\u9898\u7684\u63d0\u4ea4\u5c06\u4f1a\u88ab\u76f4\u63a5\u5173\u95ed ) ([Language Policy](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/issues/5910)).\n- [x] Please do not modify this template :) and fill in all the required fields.\n\n### Is your feature request related to a problem?\n\n```Markdown\nYes. The Xinference Go chat provider is tracked in #14808, but the initial chat-provider scope leaves Embed as a stub that returns \"no such method\".\n\nXinference supports embedding models through an OpenAI-compatible embeddings endpoint at /v1/embeddings. The official docs say the Embeddings API mimics OpenAI's create embeddings API, while also noting that LLMs themselves do not provide the Embeddings API. That means RAGFlow needs a real Xinference Embed implementation for models launched with embedding capability, while keeping chat-only LLMs separate.\n\nWithout this follow-up, a tenant can configure Xinference for chat in the Go layer but cannot use a Xinference-hosted embedding model for indexing or retrieval.\n```\n\n### Describe the feature you'd like\n\nImplement `XinferenceModel.Embed` in `internal/entity/models/xinference.go` so embedding models served by a tenant's Xinference instance work end to end.\n\nThe driver should:\n\n- POST to `/v1/embeddings` on the normalized tenant-supplied Xinference base URL.\n- Accept a model name / model UID and a list of input texts.\n- Send the OpenAI-compatible request shape: `model` plus `input`.\n- Return `[]EmbeddingData` with one vector per input, in the same order as the input texts.\n- Validate response indices so duplicate, missing, or out-of-range `data[*].index` values fail clearly instead of silently returning wrong vectors.\n- Use the same optional-auth behavior as the chat provider: only set `Authorization: Bearer <api_key>` when a non-empty key is configured.\n- Use a bounded non-streaming request timeout, matching the existing provider patterns.\n\nThe provider config should include the embedding suffix:\n\n```json\n\"url_suffix\": {\n  \"chat\": \"chat/completions\",\n  \"models\": \"models\",\n  \"embedding\": \"embeddings\"\n}\n```\n\nNo new public API. No ModelDriver interface change. This is a follow-up implementation behind the existing `Embed` method.\n\n### Describe implementation you've considered\n\nFollow the OpenAI-compatible embedding implementations already present in the Go layer, while preserving Xinference-specific behavior:\n\n- normalize `http://host:9997` and `http://host:9997/v1` to the same `/v1` base before appending `embeddings`;\n- keep API key optional because default Xinference deployments run without auth;\n- do not treat chat LLMs as embedding models, because the Xinference docs explicitly separate embedding-capable models from LLMs.\n\n### Documentation, adoption, use case\n\n```Markdown\nNo new public RAGFlow API is required. Xinference's model list is dynamic because tenants launch their own models, so the config only needs URL suffix support.\n\nUse case: a tenant runs Xinference locally, launches an embedding model such as bge-m3 or bge-small-en-v1.5, and configures RAGFlow to use that model for dataset indexing. With this change, the Go layer calls the real Xinference /v1/embeddings endpoint and returns vectors to the ingestion pipeline.\n```\n\n### Additional information\n\nTracking issue: #14736\nXinference chat provider issue: #14808\nXinference embeddings docs: https://inference.readthedocs.io/en/latest/models/model_abilities/embed.html\nXinference built-in embedding models: https://inference.readthedocs.io/en/latest/models/builtin/embedding/index.html\n\n",
